unit.name: 82 Airborne Division HQ
unit.History: The 82nd Division was formed in August 1917 in Camp Gordon, Georgia. Its recruits came from all 48 states, so it was nicknamed 'All American Division'. It saw action in France in 1918, and demobilized at the end of WW I. The division was reactivated in March 1942, and in August in became the first US Airborne Division. In July 1943 the division first saw action when it made a combat jump into Sicily. In September, the 504th Para Infantry Regiment of the division jumped into the Salerno beachhead at less than 24 hr notice, to prevent a German breakthrough. The division was then sent to England to prepare for D-Day. It jumped into Normandy on June 6, and was in combat for 33 days afterward, taking over 5000 casualties. Brought back up to strength, it took part in operation Market-Garden, and secured the important bridges at Nijmegen and Grave. By this time, it had established a reputation as arguably the best Allied division in the ETO. In December 1944, the 82nd Division, together with the 101st Division, constituted the Allied strategic reserve. When the scope of the German counterattack became clear, they were rushed to the Ardennes to help stop the German advance.

commander.Name: James M. Gavin
commander.PersBio: Nicknamed 'Slim Jim' or 'the jumping General', Gavin was born in 1907 in Brooklyn, NY, and adopted into a Pennsylvania miner's family. He enlisted into the Army in 1924, and entered West Point a year later, graduating in 1929. In 1941 he became an instructor at the newly founded Airborne School at Fort Benning, and from August 1942 he commanded the 505th Para Infantry Regiment. With the regiment he first saw action in Sicily, making his first combat jump. His next jump was at the Salerno bridgehead, where the 505th was dropped succesfully near Capua, His regiment was then taken to England to prepare for D-Day. On June 6, Gavin and the 505th jumped into Normandy. In August 1944, Gavin became commander of the 82nd Airborne Division. A month later, his division was in action again, this time in the Netherlands, where they jumped near Nijmegen, and managed to secure the bridges across the rivers Maas and Waal. On October 18, 1944 Gavin was promoted to Major General, thus becoming the youngest Major General to command a division since General Custer in the Civil War.
